* TIME COMPLEXITY :

- It does mean how much time a code is taking to run, it might be different in old and new computers.  Tc != Time taken.
- Time complexity means the rate at which time taken increases with respect to the input size.


* BIG O NOTATION:

- it is used to represent the time complexity in terms is O().
  for example:
              for(int i = 1; i < 5; i++); {
                System.out.println();  }
              
        in this loop, there are 3 operations/ steps, 1-condition check, 2-print statement, 3-increment i
        and this will repeat 5 times.  
        So Time Complexity will be O(5*3) = O(15)

              for(int i = 1; i < n; i++); {
                System.out.println();  }

        Time complexity for the above ex is O(n*3)

                                                         ** Rules **

- Always take the time complexity for worst case scenario,becuase it the time required to solve the complete problem. There are three cases
  worst case, Best case, Average case will be the (best + worst)/2.

- Avoid Constants- beacuse  if input size is 10^5.
        O(3n^3, 4n^2, 8) is the time complexity.
         Then TC beccomes  O(3 10^15, 4 10^10, 8),  so adding 8 does not make any significance.

- Avoid the smaller values,  beacuse from above example, 10 ^ 15 is a very big number, So adding 10 ^ 10 to 10 ^ 15 does not make any significance.


* Big 0 notation --> Worst case --> higher bound
* theata Notaion --> average case
* Omega notation --> Best case --> lower bound



Time Complexity example :

1)  for(int i = 0; i<n ; i++) {
      for(int j = 0; j<n; j++) {
          System.out.print()
      }
    }

  In this example the iteration goes like

  i = 0 , j = (1,2...n)      So the i runs N times and j runs also N times, so Tc will be O(n*n) == O(n^2)
  i = 1, j = (1,2...n)        there are 3 operations in loop, it should be in the TC , but we will avaoid , s.
  So on                      acc to the Big o natation rule --> Avoid the lower values.



** SPACE COMPLEXITY :

- It is also represented using the BIG O notation
- It counts two spaces
    > Variable spaces - one for each variable
    > Auxillary spaces - the space used to solve the problem

  example
        a = 10;
        b = 20;
        c = a + b;  ---> Auxillary Space.            So the Space complexity will be O(3). for the size of N elements Space Complexity is O(n).
